<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson3_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Superposition and Gates</title>

  <p> So far, all of our exploration of gate behavior has been with basis states (<m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{1}</m>).
    Now, it's time to learn how to calculate the outputs of gates when the inputs are in
    superposition (beyond memorizing that two H gates go into superposition and then out again!). </p>

  <section xml:id="sec-calc-superposition-visual">
    <title>Calculating Gates with Superposition Inputs</title>

    <p>To calculate how gates operate on qubits in superposition, there is a simple rule to follow: <em>Apply
      the gate separately to each possible outcome, then combine the results.</em>
    </p>

    <p>Let's start by looking at a simple example with a <c>NOT</c> gate.</p>

    <example>
      <title>Applying NOT on simple superposition state</title>
      <p>Consider the following, where a state in superposition is acted upon by a <c>NOT</c> gate.</p>

      <image source="L3.4-5050-to-NOT.png" width="30%" />

      <p>To evaluate the action of the <c>NOT</c> gate, we just perform the <c>NOT</c> action on each part
        of the superposition:</p>

      <image source="L3.4-5050-NOT-output.png" width="30%" />
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Applying NOT on complex superposition state</title>

      <p>Consider the following, where a 75%<ndash />25% superposition state is acted upon by a <c>NOT</c>
        gate.</p>

      <image source="L3.4-7525-to-NOT.png" width="30%" />

      <p>Once again, to evaluate the action of the <c>NOT</c> gate, we perform the <c>NOT</c> action on
        each part of the superposition:</p>

      <image source="L3.4-7525-NOT-output.png" width="30%" />

      <p>Note that we rearrange the outcomes as per our convention, placing ⚪ outcomes at the top
        and ⚫ at the bottom.</p>
    </example>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-z-gate">
    <title><c>Z</c> Gate</title>

    <sidebyside widths="85% 15%" valign="top">
      <p> Now we are going to explore the <c>Z</c> gate, which affects the phase of the qubit. Use
        the circuit builder to determine how the <c>Z</c> gate affects a qubit that is in the state <m>
        \ket{0}</m>
        or <m>\ket{1}</m>. Construct the following two circuits and observe the outputs. </p>
      <image source="L3.3_Z-gate.png" width="30%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <image source="Z_Explore.png" width="20%" />
    <p>Remember that to create an input of <m>\ket{1}</m>, you will need to use a <c>NOT</c> gate.</p>


    <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
      source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
      <script>
      visualizeProbabilitiesWidget({
        circuit: "Blank 1x6",
        allowedGates: "XHZ"
      });
    </script>
    </interactive>

    <exercise label="Z_truth_table_lesson3_3">
      <title>
        <c>Z</c> Truth Table </title>
      <idx>Z_truth_table</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Which answer best describes what you observed from the <c>Z</c> gate? </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>It does not have an observable effect.</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>If the input is <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>, the result will have an equal chance of measuring
              0 or 1. </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Look more closely at the bar graphs of the output.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Make the circuit and look at the bar graph below the circuit. Construct both input
          combinations using <c>NOT</c> gates, recording the answers each time.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      You might have been surprised by the answer! Because quantum state is more complex than merely
      the probability of measuring 0 or 1, this method for determining and expressing an operation's
      functionality is insufficient.
    </p>
    <p> Now, use the circuit builder above to create the following circuits and observe the
      outcomes. This will reveal the functionality of the <c>Z</c> gate on a qubit in superposition. </p>

    <!--<alert><p>WHICH
    VERSION OF THESE CIRCUITS IS PREFERRED?
  I LIKE THIS ONE, B/C 0 AND 1 STATES ARE VERY CLEAR.
  THE CONVENTION ALSO MATCHES PRIOR LESSONS.
  ANOTHER OPTION WOULD BE TO INCLUDE BOTH HERE TO REMIND THEM OF THE CONVENTION? (jen)</p></alert>-->

    <image source="Z_Explore_2.png" width="50%" />

    <!--
  <p><em>(Remember that to create an input of <m>\ket{1}</m>, you will need to use a <c>NOT</c> gate,
    as shown here:)</em></p>
  <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="75%" />
  -->

    <exercise label="Superposition Z">
      <title>
        <c>Z</c> Gate Behavior with Superposition </title>
      <idx>superpositionZ</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>What is the effect of the sequence <c>H</c>-<c>Z</c>-<c>H</c> on qubits beginning in <m>
          \ket{0}</m>
          or <m>
            \ket{1}
          </m>?</p>
        <image source="Checkpoint3.2-Z-gate-behavior-with-Superposition.png" width="66%" />
        <!--<image
        source="Z_Explore_2.png" width="50%" />-->
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>There is an equal chance of measuring 0 or 1.</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>No observable effect. </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>The same as a <c>NOT</c> gate</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <p> Now we see that <c>Z</c> does have a major effect on the system, but <em>only</em> when the
      qubit is in superposition. To get a clearer sense of the effect of the <c>Z</c> gate, let's
      work backwards and forwards based on our existing understanding of the <c>H</c> and what you
      observed in the exercise above. <ol>
        <li>For the first <c>H</c> gate, an equal superposition state is created. The first circuit
      has positive phase and the second has negative phase.</li>
        <li>Based on trying out this circuit, we see that the output is ⚫ for the
          first circuit and ⚪ for the second circuit.</li>
        <li>Working backwards, we see that the state right before the second <c>H</c> gate is an
      equal superposition state with negative phase for the first circuit and positive phase for the
      second circuit.</li>
      </ol> Putting this all together: </p>

    <image source="Z_Explore_2_Expanded.png" width="75%" />

    <p> Thus, we can see the effect of the <c>Z</c> gate on states in superposition. </p>

    <image source="Z_Gate_Effect_1.png" width="75%" />

    <p> Using the rules for applying gates on superposition states (<xref
        ref="sec-calc-superposition-visual" />), we can finally deduce the truth table for the <c>Z</c>
      gate below. I suggest adding this to your page of notes. </p>

    <image source="L3.2-Z-gate-truth-table.png" width="30%" />

    <p> It's important to remember that this truth table is only meaningful when the qubit is in
      superposition: there is no observable effect when a <c>Z</c> gate is applied to a basis state.
      So keeping this in mind will be helpful in the future when you are working with more complex
      superposition states! </p>

    <!-- <p> This truth table does not seem right <mdash /> you already observed that there is no
      observable effect when a Z gate is applied to a qubit in the <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>
    state. So why
      is the truth table expressed this way? We have to remember that the truth table is describing
      the effect of the Z gate on the full quantum state, including phase, not just the measurement
      outcomes. When a Z gate is applied to a qubit in the <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>
      \ket{1}</m> state, there is no
      change in phase, so the effect is not observable. However, when a Z gate is applied to a qubit
      in superposition, it flips the phase of the states, and the negative sign is always applied to
      the probability of the <m>\ket{1}</m> state. </p> -->

