  <p>
    <insert>
      Insert two circuits for them to calculate the output. Don't do the entanglement gate - just
      some interesting versions of <c>NOT</c>, <c>SWAP</c>, <c>H</c>, and <c>Z</c> to play with going to
    the 50/50 state
      and returning to 0, 1, or the <c>Z</c> gate making it flip. -Diana</insert>
  </p>
  -->

    <exercise label="L3_3_3 Calculate Output">
      <title>
        Practice calculating the output
      </title>
      <idx>L3_3_3_Calculate</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Calculate the output of this circuit.</p>
        <image source="L3_3_3_Calculate.png" width="75%" />
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{00}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{01}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{10}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Correct!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{11}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p> </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Think about what the output would be after each gate.
          Remember the compressed notation for more than one qubit lists qubit states from top to
          bottom.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

